The Umbral: The Necessary Absence

From a document found pinned to the door of the Midgaard Hall
of Records. No author claimed. The ink was cold to the touch.

They are shadow given permanent form. Not darkness-worshippers, not
cursed, not phantoms — people, whose bodies absorbed the
anti-light of the Black Sun Shard over generations of habitation
in the spaces adjacent to it. The change was slow. The change was
thorough. The change cannot be reversed, and they have not asked
for it to be.

An Umbral is difficult to perceive in shadow. The eye slides off
them — not invisibility, but a quality of presence that resists
direct observation. They are lighter than their frames suggest, as
though part of their substance exists somewhere the scales cannot
measure. In full light they are visible, solid, present. In darkness
they are something else — not absent, but adjacent to absence.

Their philosophy is built on a single principle: necessary
absence. What is not present shapes reality as powerfully as
what is. The silence between words carries meaning. The gap in
the record reveals what was removed. The shadow defines the shape
of the light. The Umbral do not consider themselves diminished.
They consider themselves evidence.

They maintain the shadow-archives — repositories of records,
testimony, and documentation that the institutions of Midgaard and
Kowloon prefer not to have accessible. Not stolen records. Records
that were discarded, sealed, or conveniently lost. The Umbral
collected what the powerful threw away and preserved it in the
dark.

The Gloamvault beneath Midgaard is their oldest known
habitation. They were there before the city. When the first human
builders laid foundations, they found Umbral stonework already in
place — older, deeper, and quite clearly not interested in
being excavated. The city was built on top of them. This is,
the Umbral note, a pattern.

They do not campaign for recognition. They do not protest their
exclusion from civic record. They simply continue to exist
in the spaces that the record does not acknowledge, holding the
documents that the record does not contain.

What you cannot see still has weight.
What you will not record is still true.
